Rating: 4
Only cheese cake I've ever made, and it consistently turns out so well, so I doubt I'll try another. I usually mix 1 cup of sour cream with 1/3 cup of sugar and a bit of vanilla for a frosting to hold berries in place. Then set the kids on to placing the berries on top - firecrackers exploding in the sky are a common theme. Would like to find out how to make a sour cream/chocolate sauce for a topping to be topped with raspberries.

Rating: 4
A few tipes on this fabulous recipe, which I've been making since it first appeared in Gourmet. It was a huge hit this past 4th of July, after a glorious meal of pulled pork. 1) I always use "light" (lower-fat) cream cheese and sour cream. 2) I've left out the sour cream when I forgot to buy it to no terribly ill effect. 3) We prefer a graham cracker crust, just substituting them for the chocolate wafers. 4) Since I seem to be a ditz when it comes to decorating, I have figured out a way to use toothpicks to create the star outline. It's easier with raspberries, and I prefer the flavor, but small or halved strawberries can work too.

